---
const problems = [
  {
    icon: '🔀',
    title: 'Spec drift',
    description: 'Requirements change but the spec doesn\'t. Code diverges from intent. Nobody knows what\'s actually supposed to happen.',
  },
  {
    icon: '🤖',
    title: 'Unreliable AI output',
    description: 'AI generates code confidently. Without a validation gate, you can\'t tell if it followed your intent or invented something plausible.',
  },
  {
    icon: '📄',
    title: 'Google Docs nobody reads',
    description: 'Long-form specs that live in Notion or Confluence. Outdated the moment they\'re written. Ignored during development.',
  },
  {
    icon: '🌀',
    title: 'Philosophy-implementation gap',
    description: 'Why the product exists and how it\'s built become disconnected. Features get added that contradict the original vision.',
  },
];
---

<section data-test="problem-section" class="py-20 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 bg-slate-50 dark:bg-slate-800/50">
  <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto">
    <div class="text-center mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white mb-4">
        The problems specs are supposed to solve
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
        Most teams have a spec process. Few have one that actually works when it counts.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-6">
      {problems.map((problem) => (
        <div class="bg-white dark:bg-slate-800 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
          <div class="text-3xl mb-4">{problem.icon}</div>
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white mb-2">{problem.title}</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">{problem.description}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
